summary: DJ Harvey (5’11/190) represents the "technician’s ideal" at cornerback, having anchored the Washington secondary with a "sticky" man-coverage profile throughout 2025. This former USC and San Jose State standout excels at pattern-matching, utilizing "patient hands" and elite hip fluidity to neutralize shifty vertical threats. While his lack of "freakish" height can make him a target for larger "X" receivers in the red zone, his recovery speed and 12 career pass deflections highlight a high-end starter's floor. After a "dominant" Senior Bowl showing where he erased top-tier wideouts in one-on-ones, Harvey’s stock is firmly in the Day 2 conversation. He is a pro-ready "nickel" or boundary hybrid with the IQ to stabilize an NFL secondary immediately.

name: Jalen Stroman
summary: Jalen Stroman (6’1”, 210 lbs) brings versatility to the secondary, posting 80+ tackles, tackles for loss, and pass breakups while aligning at safety and nickel. He’s physical in the box, effective blitzing, and competitive in coverage underneath. Deep range is adequate but not elite, making role clarity important. Stroman earned All-Conference honors for his production and consistency. He projects as a Round 4–5 pick, with early contribution on special teams and sub-packages, and a clear path to starting snaps in hybrid safety roles.

name: C.J. Donaldson
summary: C.J. Donaldson (frequently referred to as CJ Donald in scouting circles) is a physically imposing, 6'2", 232-pound running back who transferred to Ohio State for his 2025 senior season. A former tight end, he retains a "bruiser" mentality, excelling in short-yardage and red-zone situations where he recorded 10 rushing touchdowns despite a shared backfield. While he lacks elite lateral twitch, his "speed-to-power" profile and experience as a reliable receiver make him a functional three-down prospect. Scouts value his ball security and high-effort pass protection, though his 3.8 yards per carry in 2025 suggests limited "home run" potential at the next level. Currently projected as a Day 3 value pick, Donaldson offers a high-floor, rotational "power back" profile for gap-scheme NFL offenses.

name: Nick Barrett
summary: Nick Barrett (6’5”, 265 lbs) operates as a high-effort edge defender, finishing with 5+ sacks and consistent pressure production. He wins with motor, length, and physicality rather than burst, setting a firm edge against the run. Barrett lacks elite bend and closing speed, which caps his pass-rush ceiling, but his reliability stands out. Without Senior Bowl exposure, he remains more projection-based. He profiles as a Round 6–7 pick, contributing early as a rotational edge and special teams player, with staying power as depth along the defensive front.

name: Jalen Huskey
summary: Jalen Huskey (6’1/195) functions as a "sticky" man-coverage specialist who utilized a productive 2025 season at Maryland to showcase elite diagnostic instincts. During the 2026 Shrine Bowl practice sessions, Huskey impressed scouts with multiple pass breakups and a rare ability to "click-and-close" on short-area targets. While he needs to continue refining his tackling consistency against larger "power" receivers, his recovery speed and "ball-hawk" mentality make him a defensive coordinator’s dream for nickel or boundary roles. Currently trending as a late-round sleeper, Huskey offers the rare length and "alpha" competitive grit required to stabilize an NFL sub-package. He is a pro-ready playmaker with the diagnostic skills to become a consistent turnover generator at the next level.

name: Curtis Allen
summary: Curtis Allen (6’2/215) is a physically imposing running back who dominated the 2025 season, earning the Harlon Hill Trophy and Walter Camp DII Player of the Year honors. Known as "The Quiet Storm," Allen combines elite vision, patience, and power to turn routine plays into explosive gains, evidenced by his record-breaking 2,409 rushing yards and 30 touchdowns. Scouts view him as a "D2 Derrick Henry" due to his ability to break tackles and maintain breakaway speed, highlighted by multiple 80-plus yard runs. While he transitioned from a supporting role to a national standout, his consistency—rushing for over 100 yards in every game—demonstrates a high floor. His rare blend of size and production makes him a premier small-school prospect.

name: Athan Kaliakmanis
summary: Athan Kaliakmanis (6’3/212 est.) served as Rutgers’ starting quarterback in 2025, completing passes with good accuracy, quick release, and mobility to extend plays. Solid arm strength and timing-route throws appeared in consistent production. Developmental pocket passer with backup potential. Decision-making under pressure and pre-snap processing remain inconsistent; happy feet and hold-the-ball tendencies surface against blitzes; arm talent is solid but not elite. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as developmental backup if mechanics and reads are refined.

name: Diego Pavia
summary: Diego Pavia (5’11”, 205 lbs) brings toughness, competitiveness, and playmaking instincts under center, accounting for 3,000+ total yards and 30+ touchdowns as both a passer and runner. He thrives off-script, extending plays and punishing defenses with his legs, while showing improving anticipation as a thrower. Arm strength and size limit his ceiling, but his leadership and edge stand out. Pavia projects as a Round 6–7 pick or priority free agent, offering early value as a QB3 and scout-team weapon, with upside as a high-end backup in a movement-based offense.

name: Justin Jefferson
summary: Justin Jefferson (6’1”, 200 lbs) brings competitiveness and awareness to the secondary, finishing with 60+ tackles, pass breakups, and occasional turnover production. He plays with good eye discipline, takes solid angles, and communicates well on the back end. Jefferson isn’t a high-end athlete and can be tested vertically, but his reliability shows up snap to snap. He projects as a Round 6–7 pick, offering early contribution on special teams and as safety/nickel depth, with value in split-safety and zone-heavy systems.

name: Nyjalik Kelly
summary: Nyjalik Kelly (6’4/255 est.) rotated on UCF’s edge in 2025, adding tackles, TFLs, and pressures with quick first step and violent hand usage. Versatile alignment options and high motor showed in pass-rush and run-defense snaps. Developmental edge with starter traits if strength and bend improve. Bend and corner speed remain average vs. quicker tackles; pass-rush plan is power-heavy with limited counters; leverage issues occur when pad level rises. Mid-to-late Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as rotational disruptor in schemes that value motor and hand usage.

name: Namdi Obiazor
summary: Namdi Obiazor (6’1/200 est.) contributed in a secondary rotation during 2025, displaying range, tackling efficiency, and instincts in run support and coverage. Box/single-high traits and pursuit motor appeared in limited snaps. Developmental safety with depth upside. Recovery speed and burst lag against vertical threats; physicality in run support needs refinement; tackling angles in open space remain inconsistent. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth safety or special teams contributor if strength is added and coverage details are polished.

name: Drew Stevens
summary: Drew Stevens (6’0/190 est.) started as Iowa’s kicker in 2025, showing reliable accuracy on field goals, touch on kickoffs, and consistency in big moments. Developmental specialist with starter traits if leg strength and range are refined. Weaknesses include occasional misses from distance or in adverse weather; kickoff placement and hang time need improvement; limited experience in high-stakes scenarios. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth kicker or special teams contributor if consistency and leg power improve.

name: Scooby Williams
summary: Scooby Williams (6’2/235 est.) rotated at linebacker for Texas A&M in 2025, contributing solid range, tackling efficiency, and instincts in run defense and coverage. Sideline-to-sideline traits and pursuit motor appeared in limited snaps. Developmental off-ball linebacker with three-down potential. Physicality and shedding remain inconsistent against climbing blockers; slow reads and false steps occur in aggressive run fits; added strength and mass are needed to anchor in the box. Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth linebacker and special teams contributor if run-game technique improves.

name: Jalen McMurray
summary: Jalen McMurray (6’1”, 200 lbs) brings consistency and physicality to the secondary, finishing with 70+ tackles and multiple pass breakups. He plays under control, takes solid angles, and communicates well on the back end. McMurray lacks elite range but compensates with discipline and reliability. Without major postseason exposure, he remains a depth projection. He profiles as a Round 6–7 selection, contributing early on special teams and as a safety/nickel reserve, with value in split-safety looks.

name: Bryson Eason
summary: Bryson Eason (6’4/300 est.) rotated on Tennessee’s interior in 2025, contributing tackles, TFLs, and pocket pressure with quickness for size and power to hold ground against doubles when pad level stayed low. Multi-alignment value (3-technique to nose) and short-burst motor offer developmental upside. Leverage issues appear when pad level rises against climbing blockers; pass-rush counters stay limited with little bend vs. quicker guards; stamina drops in longer series. Mid-to-late Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft as rotational depth with potential for snaps if technique and strength improve.

name: Devin Voisin
summary: Devin Voisin is a 5'10", 187-pound "technician" from South Alabama whose draft stock is steadily gaining steam after a productive 2026 Senior Bowl week in his hometown of Mobile. A seven-year collegiate veteran who overcame a major knee injury in 2023, Voisin returned to peak form in 2025, hauling in 67 receptions for 775 yards and showcasing his reliability as a primary punt returner. Scouts are enamored with his "pro-ready" route running and elite hands, evidenced by several high-difficulty catches during Senior Bowl practices that proved he could separate against Power Four defensive backs. While he lacks elite size and "burner" speed, his high football IQ and special teams versatility make him a high-floor prospect. Currently projected as a Day 3 pick or high-priority free agent, Voisin is a favorite for teams seeking a dependable slot target and a core special teams contributor.

name: Will Ferrin
summary: Will Ferrin (6’0/190 est.) served as BYU’s starting kicker in 2025, demonstrating strong leg strength, accuracy on field goals and kickoffs, and consistency in pressure situations. Developmental specialist with starter traits if range and touch are refined. Weaknesses include occasional misses from distance or in wind; kickoff hang time and placement need polish; limited experience in high-pressure playoff environments. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth kicker or special teams contributor if leg strength and consistency translate.

name: Jamal Haynes
summary: Jamal Haynes (5’9”, 200 lbs) brings explosive versatility to the backfield, totaling 1,000+ all-purpose yards and double-digit touchdowns as both a runner and receiver. He accelerates rapidly, shows excellent burst through creases, and consistently stresses defenses in space. Haynes is undersized for sustained interior work and can be inconsistent in pass protection, but his juice is undeniable. He earned All-Conference honors and national attention for big-play production. He projects as a Round 4–5 pick, contributing immediately as a change-of-pace back, third-down weapon, and return threat in spread-oriented offenses.

name: Jack Kelly
summary: Jack Kelly (6’2/230 est.) rotated at linebacker for BYU in 2025, contributing solid range, tackling efficiency, and instincts in run defense and coverage. Sideline-to-sideline traits and pursuit motor appeared in limited snaps. Developmental off-ball linebacker with three-down potential. Physicality and shedding remain inconsistent against climbing blockers; slow reads and false steps occur in aggressive run fits; added strength and mass are needed to anchor in the box. Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth linebacker and special teams contributor if run-game technique improves.

name: Collin Wright
summary: Collin Wright (6’1/190 est.) started at corner for Stanford in 2025, recording 33 tackles, 5 passes defended, and 1 interception while showing physicality, ball skills, and versatility in outside/nickel roles. Quick feet, competitive press technique, and instincts in zone/match coverage appeared. Developmental corner with boundary/slot upside. Recovery speed and burst lag against vertical threats; tackling angles in open space remain inconsistent; technique lapses occur during transitions. Mid-to-late Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth corner or special teams contributor if strength is added and coverage details are refined.

name: Max Bredeson
summary: Max Bredeson (6'2", 250 lbs) is a throwback "utility" prospect from Michigan who has redefined the fullback position for the modern era. The 2025 Lowman Trophy winner as the nation's top fullback, Bredeson is a two-time captain whose value lies in his elite run-blocking, consistently earning high PFF grades for his ability to pave lanes in short-yardage situations. While his career stats of 12 receptions for 132 yards won't jump off the page, his reliability as a lead blocker and special teams ace has made him an indispensable "glue guy." Currently projected as a sixth-round pick or high-priority free agent, scouts view him as a high-floor specialist whose physical "old-school" style and leadership are tailor-made for teams looking to bolster their ground game and special teams units.

name: Vinny Anthony II
summary: Vinny Anthony II is an ascending wide receiver prospect from Wisconsin whose draft stock significantly improved after a standout week at the 2026 Senior Bowl. Standing 6'0" and 183 pounds, Anthony impressed scouts in Mobile with a sophisticated release package and the play-strength to haul in catches away from his frame in tight coverage. While his 2025 production was modest—tallying 31 receptions for 391 yards—his versatility is a primary draw; he is a dangerous return specialist with a 95-yard kickoff return touchdown against Alabama to his credit. Scouts view him as a refined route-runner with elite hands who can contribute immediately on special teams. Currently projected as a late-round pick (6th–7th round), Anthony is one of only two Badgers invited to the 2026 NFL Combine, where he looks to solidify his place on Day 3.

name: Tanner Arkin
summary: Tanner Arkin (6’5/245 est.) contributed as a rotational tight end for Illinois in 2025, showing receptions in seam and red-zone roles with reliable hands and blocking effort on short-yardage plays. Route nuance and leaping at the catch point appeared in limited production. Developmental in-line/move tight end with receiving traits and every-down value. Blocking technique and anchor remain inconsistent against power edges; height advantage is limited in contested situations; vertical speed to stretch seams is modest. Day 3 projection (Round 4-6) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as rotational TE2/TE3 if blocking hand placement is refined and strength is added.

name: Jackie Marshall
summary: Jackie Marshall (6’3/290 est.) rotated in Baylor’s interior snaps in 2025, adding tackles, TFLs, and pocket pressure in run and pass phases. Quickness for size, active hands to disengage, and power to anchor against doubles stood out when pad level stayed low. Developmental 3-technique/nose tackle with multi-alignment value and high motor in short bursts. Leverage issues arise when pad level rises against climbing blockers; pass-rush counters are limited with little bend against quicker guards; stamina drops in extended reps. Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as rotational depth if technique is refined and strength is added.

name: Mark Gronowski
summary: Mark Gronowski (6’3/215 est.) served as Iowa’s quarterback in 2025, completing passes with good accuracy, quick release, and mobility to extend plays in limited action. Dual-threat traits and timing-route throws appeared in spot duty. Developmental quarterback with backup potential. Decision-making under pressure and pre-snap processing remain inconsistent; happy feet and hold-the-ball tendencies surface against blitzes; arm talent is solid but not elite. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as developmental backup if mechanics and reads are refined.

name: Kejon Owens
summary: Kejon Owens (often referred to as Kevon Owens in draft circles) is a 5’11", 210-pound running back from FIU who skyrocketed up draft boards following a historic 2025 senior campaign. Named the CUSA Offensive Player of the Year, Owens finished the season ranked 10th nationally in rushing yards, headlined by dominant performances like his 195-yard outing against WKU. Scouts laud his elite "processing" and contact balance, describing him as a natural runner who seamlessly identifies cutback lanes and maintains momentum through glancing blows. While his top-end speed is respectable, his "piston-like" leg drive in short-yardage situations has defined his "bruiser" reputation. Currently projected as a Day 3 sleeper or priority free agent, Owens’ high-level production and reliable hands make him a potential rotational back for NFL teams seeking backfield depth.

name: Haynes King
summary: Haynes King (6’3/215) is a high-ceiling developmental prospect who pairs elite vertical speed and a quick release with natural leadership and "clutch" playmaking. While his athleticism allows him to extend plays and stress defenses, he struggles with inconsistent accuracy on short-to-intermediate throws and a "gunslinger" mentality that leads to costly turnovers. His lean frame raises significant durability concerns, especially given his tendency to abandon mechanics under pressure. Ultimately, King offers the raw tools of a franchise starter but requires a patient organization to refine his fundamentals; without significant development, his floor is that of a specialized gadget player rather than a reliable NFL centerpiece.

name: Chip Trayanum
summary: Chip Trayanum (5’11/205 est.) contributed as a rotational running back for Toledo in 2025, showing quick burst, vision in finding cutback lanes, and yards after contact in limited touches. Patience to let blocks develop and elusiveness in space appeared. Developmental change-of-pace back with committee upside. Limited volume in complementary role; ball security concerns under contact; pass-protection technique needs refinement against blitzers; lacks power to handle loaded boxes consistently. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth RB or special teams contributor if vision and elusiveness translate.

name: Kendrick Law
summary: Kendrick Law (5’11”, 185 lbs) adds speed and versatility to the receiver room, producing 600+ yards and explosive-play efficiency while aligning both outside and in motion. He accelerates quickly, tracks the ball well, and stresses defenses vertically and on crossers. Law can struggle against physical press coverage and isn’t a high-volume contested-catch option, but his speed changes coverage rules. He projects as a Round 6 pick, contributing early as a situational deep threat, gadget player, and return option, with upside in spread or play-action offenses.

name: Eric Gentry
summary: Eric Gentry (6’6”, 235 lbs) stands out immediately due to his rare length, range, and coverage ability at linebacker, finishing with 70+ tackles, tackles for loss, and pass breakups. He covers ground effortlessly, disrupts throwing lanes, and looks natural dropping into zone coverage. Gentry can struggle taking on blocks and playing through congestion, but his athletic profile is unique. He earned All-Conference recognition and flashed in postseason evaluations. He projects as a Round 3–4 pick, contributing early in sub-packages, special teams, and coverage roles, with clear starter upside as a modern NFL linebacker.

name: J.Michael Sturdivant
summary: J.Michael Sturdivant (6’3/205) operates as a physically dominant boundary target who utilizes a massive catch radius to "envelop" smaller NFL-caliber corners. This lean, long-striding athlete thrives in the red zone, leveraging his track-and-field background to turn 50-50 balls into high-percentage receptions. While he must improve his initial burst off the line and route-tree nuances, his 20+ MPH play speed and "reliable" possession numbers solidify a late Day 2 grade. Sturdivant offers the elite high-pointing ability and "pro-ready" frame required for a primary goal-line fade target. He is a unique high-ceiling weapon for a pro offense.

name: Desmond Reid
summary: Desmond Reid is an electrifying, diminutive playmaker whose versatility as a "human highlight reel" has defined his draft profile. Standing 5’8” and weighing 175 pounds, the Pittsburgh star is an elite dual-threat weapon, finishing the 2025 season with over 1,500 all-purpose yards and 14 touchdowns. Scouts rave about his world-class acceleration and "stop-on-a-dime" agility, which allows him to thrive as a receiver out of the slot and a dynamic punt returner. While his small frame raises durability concerns and limits his pass-protection upside, his explosive playmaking ability draws comparisons to Darren Sproles. Currently projected as a Day 2 or early Day 3 pick, Reid is viewed as a high-upside "gadget" weapon who can immediately transform an NFL team's special teams and sub-package offense.

name: George Gumbs Jr
summary: George Gumbs Jr (6’4/250) emerged as a "high-octane" disruptor for Florida in 2025, recording 31 tackles, 6.5 TFLs, and 2.5 sacks in just nine games. This former wide receiver-turned-edge specialist utilizes "freakish" athletic tools and a slippery speed-to-power transition to harass quarterbacks, showcasing the bend needed to "run the hoop" against elite SEC tackles. While he remains "raw" in his diagnostic processing against the run, his 48 total pressures and "non-stop" pursuit motor highlight a legitimate Day 2 developmental ceiling. Currently trending as a "high-upside" riser, Gumbs offers the rare length and vertical twitch needed to become a primary situational pass-rusher. He is a premier "chess piece" for creative defensive coordinators in the 2026 cycle.

name: Zavion Thomas
summary: Zavion Thomas (5’10/192) functions as a "human joystick" who utilized his 4.32-speed to revitalize LSU’s vertical and return games in 2025. This shifty, explosive separator thrives on designed touches and underneath routes, turning routine catches into chunk gains through elite acceleration. While his diminutive frame limits his red-zone utility, his vision as a return specialist and versatility to align in the slot make him a primary gadget weapon. Following a productive Senior Bowl showing, Thomas profiles as a Day 3 value. He is the quintessential "chain-mover" for creative offensive coordinators in 2026.

name: Eli Heidenreich
summary: Eli Heidenreich (6’0/190 est.) contributed as a rotational wide receiver for Navy in 2025, showing reliable hands, intermediate separation, and yards after catch on slants/screens. Route nuance and body control appeared in limited production. Developmental slot/outside receiver with dependable traits. Size aids contested-catch situations; production remains modest; press coverage at the line creates inconsistency. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth piece or special teams contributor if releases are refined and strength is added.

name: Emmanuel Henderson
summary: Emmanuel Henderson (5’11”, 200 lbs) brings explosive ability to the backfield, totaling 700+ rushing yards, receiving production, and return value. He shows excellent acceleration, creativity in space, and the ability to flip field position. Henderson’s size limits durability concerns and pass-protection reliability, but his playmaking stands out. He projects as a Round 6–7 pick, contributing early as a change-of-pace back, return specialist, and offensive weapon, particularly in spread or tempo-based systems.

name: Wesley Bissainthe
summary: Wesley Bissainthe (6’2/230 est.) rotated at linebacker for Miami in 2025, contributing solid range, tackling efficiency, and instincts in run defense and coverage. Sideline-to-sideline traits and pursuit motor appeared in limited snaps. Developmental off-ball linebacker with three-down potential. Physicality and shedding remain inconsistent against climbing blockers; slow reads and false steps occur in aggressive run fits; added strength and mass are needed to anchor in the box. Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth linebacker and special teams contributor if run-game technique improves.

name: Jaylon Guilbeau
summary: Jaylon Guilbeau (5’10/180 est.) appeared in Texas’ nickel and boundary packages in 2025, showing quick feet, competitive ball skills, and solid run support in rotational reps. Press technique at the line, mirroring underneath, and instincts in zone/match coverage showed promise. Athletic profile and competitive traits fit as a developmental corner with nickel/slot upside. Recovery speed and burst lag against vertical threats; tackling angles in open space remain inconsistent; technique lapses occur during coverage transitions. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth corner or special teams contributor if strength is added and coverage details are refined.

name: Marcus Allen
summary: Marcus Allen (5’11/185 est.) contributed in North Carolina’s secondary rotation in 2025, showing quick feet, competitive ball skills, and solid run support in nickel and boundary snaps. Press technique at the line, mirroring underneath, and instincts in zone/match coverage showed promise. Developmental corner with nickel/slot upside. Recovery speed and burst lag against vertical threats; tackling angles in open space remain inconsistent; technique lapses occur during transitions. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth corner or special teams contributor if strength is added and coverage details are refined.

name: Trey Smack
summary: Trey Smack (6’1/201) stands as the premiere specialist of the 2026 class, having solidified his "deadly" accuracy and range during a standout 2025 season at Florida. Recording multiple 50-plus yard field goals—including a career-long 56-yarder—Smack combines a "piston-like" leg with elite mental composure in high-leverage situations. While most kickers struggle with the jump to NFL-style pressure, his "kickoff-specialist" background and 82% career field-goal rate suggest a Day 1 pro floor. After a "perfect" week in Mobile where he routinely hit from 60 yards in practice, Smack is trending toward a rare fourth-round selection. He is a "franchise-leg" prospect with the leg-strength to erase field-position disadvantages and win games from the logo.

name: Dominic Zvada
summary: Dominic Zvada (6’0/190 est.) served as Michigan’s starting kicker in 2025, showing strong leg strength, accuracy on field goals and kickoffs, and consistency in pressure situations. Developmental specialist with starter traits if range and touch are refined. Weaknesses include occasional misses from distance or in wind; kickoff hang time and placement need polish; limited experience in high-pressure playoff environments. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth kicker or special teams contributor if leg strength and consistency translate.

name: Austin Brown
summary: Austin Brown (6’4”, 290 lbs) offers interior flexibility along the defensive line, contributing tackles for loss and pocket disruption that often doesn’t show in sack totals. He plays with good leverage, active hands, and a steady motor, particularly effective on stunts and movement fronts. Brown can struggle anchoring against double teams, limiting his early-down usage. He projects as a Round 6 pick, contributing early as a rotational interior lineman, with upside in sub-packages that emphasize penetration and movement.

name: Malik Benson
summary: Malik Benson (6’1/195 est.) transferred to Florida State in 2025 and served as a rotational boundary receiver, showing reliable hands, intermediate separation, and yards after catch on slants/screens. Route nuance and body control appeared in limited production. Developmental slot/outside receiver with dependable traits. Size aids contested-catch situations; production remains modest; press coverage at the line creates inconsistency. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth piece or special teams contributor if releases are refined and strength is added.

name: Behren Morton
summary: Behren Morton is a 6'2", 215-pound "gunslinger" who solidified his draft stock by leading Texas Tech to its first-ever Big 12 Championship in 2025. Despite battling recurring injuries, he recorded a career-high 66% completion percentage, totaling 2,780 yards and 22 touchdowns. Morton is lauded for his "live arm," clean mechanics, and the ability to vary arm angles in off-schedule situations. While his accuracy and "improv" skills thrive in the short-to-intermediate game, scouts remain wary of his inconsistent pocket presence and "slingshot" delivery, which can lead to batted balls. One of 15 quarterbacks invited to the 2026 NFL Scouting Combine, Morton is currently projected as a Day 3 developmental project (6th round) with the high-ceiling traits necessary to be a long-term NFL backup or "heir apparent."

name: Caden Fordham
summary: Caden Fordham (6’4”, 235 lbs) profiles as a modern receiving tight end, producing 30+ receptions, 400+ yards, and multiple touchdowns while working seams and underneath zones. He moves fluidly for his size, flashes natural hands, and understands spacing against coverage. Fordham’s blocking technique and strength remain developmental, particularly versus NFL edge defenders, but effort is consistent. He stayed under the radar without Senior Bowl exposure. He projects as a Round 6 pick, contributing early as a TE3 and situational receiver, with upside if his functional strength improves.

name: Dalton Johnson
summary: Dalton Johnson (6’3”, 235 lbs) plays with physicality and discipline at linebacker, finishing with 90+ tackles, tackles for loss, and pressure production as a blitzer. He reads keys quickly, fills downhill with authority, and brings leadership to the front seven. Johnson’s lateral range is adequate rather than dynamic, and coverage ability is role-dependent. He earned All-Conference recognition for consistent production. He projects as a Round 5–6 pick, contributing early on special teams and early-down defense, with rotational starter potential in base packages.

name: Jackson Kuwatch
summary: Jackson Kuwatch (6’4/250 est.) rotated on Miami (OH)’s edge in 2025, adding tackles, TFLs, and pressures with quick first step and power bull rush. Versatile alignment options and high motor showed in pass-rush and run-defense snaps. Developmental edge with starter traits if strength and bend improve. Bend and corner speed remain average vs. quicker tackles; pass-rush plan is power-heavy with limited counters; leverage issues occur when pad level rises. Mid-to-late Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as rotational disruptor in schemes that value motor and power.

name: Bauer Sharp
summary: Bauer Sharp (6’5/245 est.) contributed as a rotational tight end for LSU in 2025, showing receptions in seam and red-zone roles with reliable hands and blocking effort on short-yardage plays. Route nuance and leaping at the catch point appeared in limited production. Developmental in-line/move tight end with receiving traits and every-down value. Blocking technique and anchor remain inconsistent against power edges; height advantage is limited in contested situations; vertical speed to stretch seams is modest. Day 3 projection (Round 4-6) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as rotational TE2/TE3 if blocking hand placement is refined and strength is added.

name: Jeff Caldwell
summary: Jeff Caldwell (6’2/195 est.) contributed as a rotational wide receiver for Cincinnati in 2025, showing reliable hands, intermediate separation, and yards after catch on slants/screens. Route nuance and body control appeared in limited production. Developmental slot/outside receiver with dependable traits. Size aids contested-catch situations; production remains modest; press coverage at the line creates inconsistency. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth piece or special teams contributor if releases are refined and strength is added.

name: Kentrel Bullock
summary: Kentrel Bullock is a 5'10", 205-pound "one-cut-and-go" runner from South Alabama who enters the 2026 draft cycle as a record-breaking production leader. After transferring from Ole Miss, Bullock cemented his legacy in 2025 by setting the Jaguars' single-season rushing record with 1,085 yards and 14 touchdowns, earning First-Team All-Sun Belt honors. Scouts are enamored with his explosive upfield burst and elite contact balance, noting his ability to remain upright through glancing blows while maintaining "track-sprinter" movement in the open field. While he has significantly improved his ball security—not fumbling once during his 218-carry senior campaign—questions remain regarding his hip fluidity and pass-protection ceiling. Currently projected as a Day 3 value pick (Round 6-7), Bullock’s invitation to the East-West Shrine Bowl suggests his physical, touchdown-scoring profile has high-priority interest from NFL gap-scheme offenses.

name: Michael Wortham
summary: Michael Wortham (5’9/190) emerged as the "FCS Darling" of the 2026 cycle, setting a program record with over 2,400 all-purpose yards for Montana in 2025. This "shifty" slot-weapon functions as a defensive coordinator’s nightmare, capable of aligning at receiver, running back, or even wildcat quarterback. While his diminutive frame restricts him to a "rotational" NFL role, his elite change-of-direction and 11.0 yards-per-touch average highlight a "game-breaking" floor. After proving he could handle Power-4 physical competition during the Senior Bowl, Wortham has solidified a fourth-round grade. He is the quintessential "Swiss Army Knife" for creative offenses, offering immediate high-end utility as both a return specialist and an open-field playmaker.

name: Joe Fagnano
summary: Joe Fagnano (6’2”, 225 lbs) brings experience and toughness to the quarterback position, operating efficiently in a timing-based offense while accounting for 2,400+ passing yards and 20+ total touchdowns. He’s comfortable working the middle of the field, shows good touch on short and intermediate throws, and protects the football. Arm strength is average and he’s not a creator outside structure, but his poise stands out. Fagnano projects as a Round 6–7 pick or priority free agent, offering early value as a QB3 and scout-team operator, with backup upside in West Coast-style systems.

name: Dean Connors
summary: Dean Connors is a 6'0", 208-pound "all-purpose" back whose stock soared after a dominant 2026 East-West Shrine Bowl performance. A transfer from Rice to Houston, Connors capped his 2025 senior season with 977 rushing yards and 9 total touchdowns, proving his durability as a lead back. Scouts laud his "sure-handed" reliability—remaining turnover-free throughout his career—and his sophisticated route-running, which saw him haul in 139 passes over the last three seasons. While he lacks a true "getaway" gear for long-distance scores, his patience behind blockers and physical "churn" through contact have him trending as a viable RB2 at the next level. Previously overlooked, Connors is now a Day 3 riser likely to be selected in the 5th or 6th round by a team seeking a pro-ready, three-down contributor.

name: TJ Guy
summary: TJ Guy (6’4/250 est.) rotated on Michigan’s edge in 2025, adding tackles, TFLs, and pressures with quick first step and violent hand usage. Versatile alignment options and high motor showed in pass-rush and run-defense snaps. Developmental edge with starter traits if strength and bend improve. Bend and corner speed remain average vs. quicker tackles; pass-rush plan is power-heavy with limited counters; leverage issues occur when pad level rises. Mid-to-late Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as rotational disruptor in schemes that value motor and hand usage.

name: Noah Thomas
summary: Noah Thomas (6’6/200) stands out as a "towering" boundary weapon who utilized a 2025 transfer to Georgia to showcase elite red-zone utility. This long-striding target excels at high-pointing the football, leveraging his massive catch radius to "neutralize" smaller corners in contested-catch scenarios. While he lacks the "explosive" short-area twitch of a primary separator, his 15.9 yards-per-reception average and improved route-stems suggest a high-floor possession role. Following a productive draft cycle that highlighted his reliable hands, Thomas projects as a mid-round gem. He offers the prototypical "above-the-rim" traits needed for an NFL "X" receiver role.

name: Carson Ryan
summary: Carsen Ryan (6’4/250) solidified his status as a "quarterback’s best friend" during BYU’s historic 11-win 2025 season. This former Utah and UCLA standout operates as a polished "Y-iso" target, utilizing elite body control and reliable hands to record multiple red-zone touchdowns. While he lacks the "explosive" vertical speed of a primary deep-threat, his 15.1 yards-per-catch average and high-IQ ability to exploit zone soft spots impressed scouts during the recent showcase circuit. Following a 2025 campaign where he served as a primary blocking anchor in the Big 12, Ryan has solidified a Day 3 grade. He possesses the professional frame and veteran "cool" required to become a reliable second tight end in a heavy-set NFL personnel grouping.

name: Jordan Hudson
summary: Jordan Hudson (6’0”, 185 lbs) brings burst and versatility to the receiver position, contributing explosive plays, jet motion usage, and return production. He threatens defenses horizontally, shows quick acceleration, and can uncover on short routes. Hudson lacks size and struggles through contact, limiting contested-catch situations. He projects as a Round 6–7 pick or priority free agent, contributing early as a gadget receiver and return option, with upside if he expands his route tree and play strength.

name: Ceyair Wright
summary: Ceyair Wright (5’11/185 est.) started at corner for Nebraska in 2025, recording tackles, pass breakups, and interceptions while showing quick feet, competitive press technique, and instincts in zone/match coverage. name: Kendal Daniels
summary: Kendal Daniels (6’2/205 est.) contributed in Oklahoma’s secondary in 2025, showing range, tackling efficiency, and instincts in run support and coverage. name: Patrick Payton
summary: Patrick Payton (6’5”, 250 lbs) flashes high-end edge traits, combining length, burst, and power while producing double-digit sacks and tackles for loss. Run defense remains a growth area, but the pass-rush juice is real. He projects as a Round 2–3 selection, offering immediate value as a rotational pass rusher, with starter upside as his run-game consistency improves.

name: Dillon Bell
summary: Dillon Bell (6’1/210 est.) transitioned to a rotational wide receiver role for Georgia in 2025 after prior snaps at tight end, showing reliable hands, intermediate separation, and yards after catch on slants/screens. name: Squirrel White
summary: Squirrel White (5’10/175 est.) contributed in Tennessee’s slot in 2025, displaying quick separation underneath, reliable hands, and yards after catch on slants/screens. Route nuance, acceleration out of breaks, and space creation appeared in limited production. Slot traits and return potential provide developmental upside. Size and contested-catch ability limit him against physical corners; deep-threat profile remains modest; press coverage at the line creates inconsistency. Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as rotational slot piece or special teams contributor if releases are refined and strength is added.

name: Caullin Lacy
summary: Caullin Lacy is a 5'10", 190-pound dynamic playmaker from Louisville who has solidified his status as one of the premier "all-purpose" weapons in the 2026 class. After a massive 1,316-yard season at South Alabama in 2023, Lacy transferred to the ACC where he earned Third-Team All-ACC honors despite missing early time with a broken collarbone. Scouts are enamored with his "speed for days" and elite elusiveness, evidenced by the 482 yards he gained after the catch in 2025. A true special teams ace, he was a FWAA Second-Team All-American as a returner, highlighted by two punt return touchdowns and a 100-yard kickoff return score. While his smaller frame may limit him to slot duties, his "high football IQ" and ability to win in space make him a dangerous sub-package weapon. Currently a Round 4 developmental prospect, Lacy is a high-upside target for teams needing immediate special teams impact and a shifty YAC threat.

name: Will Kacmerek
summary: Will Kacmarek (6’6/258) solidified his status as a "quarterback-friendly" weapon during Ohio State’s 2025 campaign after transferring from South Dakota. Recording 15 receptions for 168 yards and two touchdowns, Kacmarek functions primarily as an elite "Y" blocker with the functional mass to stonewall Big Ten edge-rushers. While he lacks the "explosive" vertical twitch of a primary seam-stretcher, his reliable hands and "basketball-style" body control make him a primary red-zone target. Currently projected as a mid-round value, Kacmarek offers the rare competitive "grit" and technical savvy required to impact a pro running game immediately. He is the quintessential pro-ready tight end with the mass and motor to stabilize an NFL "heavy" personnel grouping.

name: Josh Moten
summary: Josh Moten (6’2”, 215 lbs) offers a balanced linebacker profile, producing 90+ tackles, tackles for loss, and coverage impact over the season. He reads quickly, flows laterally with control, and shows comfort dropping into hook and flat zones. Moten isn’t a thumper and can struggle taking on blocks inside, but his range and awareness fit today’s game. He projects as a Round 6–7 pick, contributing early on special teams and sub-packages, with upside as a rotational linebacker in space-oriented defenses.

name: Tyler Onyedim
summary: Tyler Onyedim (6’3/290 est.) rotated in Texas A&M’s interior snaps in 2025, adding tackles, TFLs, and pocket pressure in run and pass phases. Quickness for size, active hands to disengage, and power to anchor against doubles stood out when pad level stayed low. Developmental 3-technique/nose tackle with multi-alignment value and high motor in short bursts. Leverage issues arise when pad level rises against climbing blockers; pass-rush counters are limited with little bend against quicker guards; stamina drops in extended reps. Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as rotational depth if technique is refined and strength is added.

name: Wydett Williams
summary: Wydett Williams (6’2/210) functions as a "range-heavy" enforcer who utilized a 2025 transfer to Ole Miss to cement his status as a premiere deep-third defender. This former ULM standout operates with a "seek-and-destroy" mentality, combining 99 career tackles with the ball-skills needed to record three interceptions in a single season. While he needs to improve his tackling consistency against heavy-set blockers, his 4.52-speed and natural diagnostic instincts against vertical SEC threats impressed evaluators during the recent showcase circuit. Currently projected as a mid-round value, Williams offers the high-floor "centerfield" safety traits and special teams floor needed to stabilize an NFL secondary. He is a pro-ready defensive general with the elite communication skills required for a starting role.

name: Ben Bell
summary: Ben Bell (6’3/255 est.) rotated on Virginia Tech’s edge in 2025, adding tackles, TFLs, and pressures with quick first step and violent hand usage. Versatile alignment options and high motor showed in pass-rush and run-defense snaps. Developmental edge with starter traits if strength and bend improve. Bend and corner speed remain average vs. quicker tackles; pass-rush plan is power-heavy with limited counters; leverage issues occur when pad level rises. Mid-to-late Day 3 projection (Round 5-7) in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as rotational disruptor in schemes that value motor and hand usage.

name: Gary Smith III
summary: Gary Smith III (6’2/340) provides a "monstrous" interior presence who anchored UCLA’s 2025 defensive line with 39 tackles and a reputation as an unmovable run-stuffing anchor. This former Duke transfer utilizes elite "knock-back" strength and a massive frame to neutralize double-teams, recording 1.5 TFLs while consistently resetting the line of scrimmage. While his pass-rush utility is limited to a "bull-rush" specialist, his ability to "clog the drain" against physical Big Ten rushing attacks has made him a favorite for 3-4 defensive coordinators. Following an active Senior Bowl where he showcased improved "post-pressure" stamina, Smith’s stock has solidified in the late-round range. He is a high-value "short-yardage" specialist with the functional mass to start immediately.

name: Ricardo Hallman
summary: Ricardo Hallman (5’11/190 est.) started at corner for Wisconsin in 2025, recording tackles, pass breakups, and interceptions while showing quick feet, competitive press technique, and instincts in zone/match coverage. name: Lance Mason
summary: Lance Mason (6’0”, 195 lbs) plays with confidence and ball awareness in the secondary, recording multiple interceptions and double-digit pass breakups. Mason can be challenged by bigger receivers in press situations, but his instincts help offset physical limitations. He profiles as a Round 5–6 pick, projecting early as a nickel depth corner and core special teamer, with potential to earn expanded coverage snaps in the right scheme.

name: Jaheim Lawson

Currently trending as a Day 3 riser, Lawson offers the rare competitive "grit" and technical savvy required to impact a pro defensive line immediately. He is a high-upside developmental prospect with the bloodlines and motor to become a double-digit sack artist.

name: Ethan Burke

Austin earned All-Conference honors for his production and consistency. While he wasn’t a Senior Bowl invitee, his tape reflects reliability. He projects as a Day 3 linebacker with early special teams impact and rotational value in run-heavy defensive packages.

name: DJ Rogers
summary: DJ Rogers (6’4/245) represents a "modern" tight end specimen who utilized his 2025 campaign at TCU to cement his status as a premier red-zone mismatch. While his in-line blocking remains a developmental hurdle, his 14.5 yards-per-reception average and ability to stretch the "seams" make him an elite "Big Slot" candidate. Following a refined Senior Bowl where he showcased improved hand-technique and "stickiness" as a route-runner, Rogers is trending toward a mid-round selection. He offers the high-upside athletic profile and massive catch radius needed to become a primary safety-valve for an NFL quarterback.

name: Dominic Bailey

name: Jordan Dwyer
summary: Jordan Dwyer is a 6'0", 190-pound "possession-plus" receiver who transitioned seamlessly from a 1,192-yard sophomore season at Idaho to becoming the primary target at TCU in 2025. Starting all 12 games for the Horned Frogs, Dwyer recorded 54 receptions for 730 yards and 7 touchdowns, proving his ability to thrive against Power Four competition. Scouts are particularly high on his "contested-catch grit" and polished route-running, often highlighting his willingness to work in traffic and his "hustle" on extended plays. While he currently deals with a nagging foot injury expected to linger until March, his high-volume production and reliable hands have established him as a productive "X" or "Z" receiver. Currently projected as a Day 3 pick or priority free agent, Dwyer enters the draft cycle as a technically sound, high-floor prospect who elevates an offense through consistency and football intelligence.

name: Rahsual Faison
summary: Rahsul Faison (5’11/217) represents a "violent" between-the-tackles hammer who spearheaded South Carolina’s ground game with 588 scrimmage yards in his 2025 breakout. This former Utah State star combines elite contact balance with a "piston-like" leg drive, earning a reputation for punishing defenders in the open field. While his "breakout age" (26) and banged-up shoulder have sparked draft-board debates, his elite 4.46-speed projection and "Sony Michel-style" wiggle make him a high-end rotational asset. After an active Senior Bowl showcasing his utility as a pass-catcher, Faison projects as a Day 3 value. He is the quintessential "finisher" for any physical NFL offense seeking a three-down bruiser with the functional mass to handle a professional workload.

name: Jalil Farooq
summary: Jalil Farooq (5’11”, 195 lbs) delivers steady, dependable production at wide receiver, totaling 600+ yards and multiple touchdowns while working inside and outside. He shows reliable hands, strong route discipline, and toughness as a blocker and over-the-middle target. Farooq lacks elite speed or suddenness, but his consistency shows up on tape. He earned All-Conference recognition and steady draft interest. He projects as a Round 5–6 selection, contributing early as a WR4, slot/outside hybrid, and special teams contributor, with value in timing-based offenses.

name: Miller Moss
summary: Miller Moss (6’2/205) salvaged his draft stock during a gutsy 2025 campaign at Louisville, recording 22 touchdowns and showcasing excellent command of a pro-style system. This "gutsy" commander operates with a high-IQ approach, utilizing rapid-fire processing and elite "clean-pocket" accuracy to distribute the ball to his weapons. While scouts note his average arm talent and "emergency QB3" physical ceiling, his improved poise under heavy pressure and "quarterback-friendly" decision-making impressed evaluators during the recent showcase circuit. Projected as a Day 3 value, Moss offers the reliable leadership and veteran "cool" needed for a backup role.

name: Keanu Tanuvasa
summary: Keanu Tanuvasa (6’4/301) functions as a high-motor defensive tackle who transitioned seamlessly to BYU for his breakout 2025 campaign. Recording multiple tackles for loss and showcasing a "slippery" first step, Tanuvasa excels at shooting gaps and disrupting pocket integrity from the 3-technique. While he lacks the massive bulk of a true nose tackle, his active hands and "non-stop" pursuit range impressed scouts during the recent showcase circuit. Projected as a mid-round value, Tanuvasa offers the scheme-diverse interior pass-rush and high-character leadership needed to stabilize a pro defensive line immediately.

name: Jalen Walthall
summary: Jalen Walthall (6’0/190 est.) contributed as a rotational wide receiver for UAB in 2025, showing quick separation, reliable hands, and yards after catch on intermediate routes. Route nuance and body control appeared in limited production. Developmental slot/outside receiver with dependable traits. Size aids contested-catch situations; production remains modest; press coverage at the line creates inconsistency. Day 3/UDFA projection in the 2026 NFL Draft with upside as depth piece or special teams contributor if releases are refined and strength is added.

name: Jordan van den Berg
summary: Jordan van den Berg (6’4”, 295 lbs) flashes interior disruption with multiple sacks and tackles for loss, showing quick hands and good leverage for his size. He penetrates effectively on stunts and twists, collapsing pockets when his timing is right. Van den Berg can struggle holding up against double teams and needs more consistency anchoring versus the run. He wasn’t a Senior Bowl headliner, but his athletic interior profile draws interest. With refinement, he projects as a rotational 3-tech defensive tackle capable of contributing in pass-rush packages and sub fronts.

name: Clay Patterson
summary: Clay Patterson (6’3/285) provides an "effort-first" interior presence who transitioned from Yale and UNLV to lead Stanford’s 2025 defensive line. Recording 4.0 sacks and 5.5 TFLs, Patterson utilizes a violent first-step and "slippery" hand usage to penetrate gaps. While he lacks the sheer mass to handle heavy NFL double-teams as a true nose, his versatility as a 3-technique makes him a valuable rotational asset. Following an active Senior Bowl week where he consistently collapsed the pocket, Patterson’s stock has risen into the Day 3 range as a high-value, high-motor interior depth piece.

Following a refined 2025 campaign where he missed just seven tackles, Harsh has emerged as a consensus top-150 prospect for 2026. Currently projected as a fringe first-round talent, Smith offers a rare blend of leadership, durability, and "whistle-to-whistle" motor. He is the high-floor defensive anchor every modern NFL coordinator covets for 2026.

Currently trending as a late-round developmental project, Castellanos offers the rare high-ceiling mobility required for a "gadget" NFL role or a specialized change-of-pace quarterback. Following a refined Senior Bowl showcasing improved decision-making, Retzlaff projects as a mid-round value. He possesses the raw "cool" and grit required for a professional backup role.

name: Conner Wegman

Currently vaulting into early Day 2 consideration, Weigman offers the "quarterback-friendly" decision-making and pro-style diagnostic skills needed to stabilize a professional huddle. Currently projected as a high Day 2 riser, Williams offers the physical "alpha" traits and massive catch radius required to become a primary boundary weapon in a pro-style offense.

name: Raylen Wilson

Wilson earned All-Conference recognition and steady draft buzz. He projects as a Round 4–5 pick, with immediate impact on special teams and early-down defense, and a path to starter reps in the right front.
